    <h2 id="what-is-gaba">What Is GABA and Why It Matters for Stress Relief</h2>

    <p>Gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) is the most abundant inhibitory neurotransmitter in the human central nervous system. While excitatory neurotransmitters like glutamate accelerate neural firing and heighten alertness, GABA does the opposite — it binds to GABA-A and GABA-B receptors on postsynaptic neurons, reducing their firing rate and producing a measurable calming effect on brain activity. This is not a subtle biochemical footnote: every prescription anxiolytic, from benzodiazepines to barbiturates, works by enhancing GABA receptor activity.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">40%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of all synapses in the human brain use GABA as their primary neurotransmitter, according to data from the <strong>National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke</strong>. When GABA activity is insufficient, the result is an overexcited nervous system — manifesting as anxiety, racing thoughts, muscle tension, and difficulty falling asleep.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The appeal of GABA gummies is straightforward: they offer a non-prescription, non-sedating way to support the same neurotransmitter system that pharmaceutical anxiolytics target, without the dependency risk, cognitive impairment, or withdrawal symptoms associated with GABAergic drugs. The key question is whether oral GABA supplementation actually produces meaningful effects — and the answer depends heavily on the form and dose used.</p>

