    <!-- INGREDIENT SCIENCE BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>The Science of GABA: How Your Brain's Calming Neurotransmitter Works</h4>
      <p>Understanding GABA's mechanism of action helps you choose the right product and set realistic expectations. GABA is not a sedative — it is a neural modulator that reduces excitatory signaling, which is a fundamentally different approach to relaxation than melatonin or antihistamine-based sleep aids.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>GABA-A Receptor Pathway</strong>
          <p>GABA binds to GABA-A receptors, opening chloride ion channels that hyperpolarize neurons and reduce their firing rate. This is the same receptor system targeted by benzodiazepines and alcohol, but supplemental GABA activates it at a far lower intensity — producing calm without impairment or dependency.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>GABA-B Receptor Pathway</strong>
          <p>GABA-B receptors are G-protein coupled receptors that modulate calcium and potassium channels. Activation reduces excitatory neurotransmitter release, contributing to muscle relaxation and reduced neural excitability. This pathway is slower-acting but longer-lasting than GABA-A.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Gut-Brain Axis Mechanism</strong>
          <p>Emerging research suggests oral GABA may exert effects through the enteric nervous system and vagus nerve signaling rather than direct BBB crossing. The gut contains GABA receptors that communicate with the central nervous system, providing an alternative pathway for oral supplementation to influence brain chemistry.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>GABA vs. L-Theanine</strong>
          <p>GABA directly inhibits neural firing; L-theanine increases alpha brain waves and modestly boosts endogenous GABA production. GABA acts faster (30-60 minutes); L-theanine provides sustained effects over 2-4 hours. Combined, they produce synergistic relaxation superior to either alone.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Optimal dosing strategy:</strong> Clinical trials consistently use 100mg of GABA (preferably PharmaGABA) as the effective dose for measurable stress reduction. Higher doses (200-250mg) may increase effects but also increase the likelihood of transient tingling. Start at 100mg for two weeks before increasing. For synergistic formulas (GABA + L-theanine), even 50mg of GABA can be effective when paired with 100-200mg of L-theanine.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

